make deepfakes), historical (e.g., what are the origins of news media), and social (e.g., how does social media change people’s perception of the truth). Homework is technical — we learn how to make our own deepfakes!\n{My work}\n2020-10-19 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://drive.google.com/file/d/17lhyP7f9aASQEsWe1rk9p1DgF5cgmXDK/view"},"insert":"Final project"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Physical Computing, Introduction"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Prof. Daniel Rozin. "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://itp.nyu.edu/physcomp/"},"insert":"Course website."},{"insert":"\nMy summary: This course is an introduction to understanding and making simple electronics circuits and IoT devices. We learn about how to calculate voltage, what resistors do, to wire things up on a breadboard, how to solder, how to debug circuits, and how to write code for an Arduino and have it interact with circuits, sensors, and computers.\n{My work}\n2020-12-16 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://itp.nyu.edu/shows/winter2020/walltap/"},"insert":"I presented my Project 3 at the Winter Show."},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-11-25 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-12-09-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 13"},{"insert":": "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Project 3"},{"insert":" final"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-10-14 — Week 12: No post!"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-11-25 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-11-25-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 11"},{"insert":": "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Project 3"},{"insert":" prototype"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-11-18 — Week 10: No post! I didn’t have the materials :("},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-11-11 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-11-11-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 9"},{"insert":": "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Project 2"},{"insert":" final"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-11-04 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-11-04-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 8"},{"insert":": I2C, "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Project 2"},{"insert":" progress"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-10-28 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-10-28-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 7"},{"insert":": More serial, "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Project 2"},{"insert":" idea"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-10-21 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-10-21-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 6"},{"insert":": Serial comms"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-10-14 — Week 5: No post!"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-10-07 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-10-07-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 4"},{"insert":": "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Project 1"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-09-30 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-09-30-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 3"},{"insert":": Speakers, servos"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-09-23 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-09-23-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 2"},{"insert":": I/O"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"2020-09-16 — "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://./posts/2020-09-16-pcomp.html"},"insert":"Week 1"},{"insert":": Breadboards, electronics, switches"},{"attributes":{"list":"bullet"},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Population Infinite: The Future of Identity"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Profs. Dan Oved & Anastasis Germanidis. "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://github.com/agermanidis/population-infinite"},"insert":"Course website."},{"insert":"\nMy summary: This course explores how technology is changing our concept of identity. We learn about how identity can be simulated, hidden, abused, redefined, repurposed, etc. Homework is technical — we learn how to use various tools that we can use to play around with identity. These tools are useful outside of this class too — they include the test automation library Puppeteer and the text ML model GPT-2.\n"},{"attributes":{"italic":true},"insert":"My work for this course is currently private but will be published here soon."},{"insert":"\nSocially Engaged Art and Digital Practice"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Prof. Clarinda MacLow. "},{"attributes":{"link":"https://www.coursicle.com/nyu/courses/ITPGGT/2156/"},"insert":"Third-party course listing."},{"insert":"\nMy summary: This course explores how technology can be used with art that acts as social commentary — both as a way of building the art and as a subject of the commentary. Homework is a written or multimedia response to the readings for each week.\n"},{"attributes":{"italic":true},"insert":"My work for this course is currently private but will be published here soon."},{"insert":"\n"}]
